Introduction¶

I chose the Ford GoBike System Data dataset covering the greater San Francisco Bay area. The data was collected during bike rides where the bikes came from a bike-sharing company. The dataset covers the years 2017 - 2019 and was downloaded on this site: https://s3.amazonaws.com/fordgobike-data/index.html. Not only does this dataset provide data on when a ride was made and how long it took but also start and end stations, which gender the users have, their year of birth and whether they had an annual subscription or not. After heaving cleaned the dataset, there are now 2,570,833 rows which are subject for my data analysis.

# creates standard bins
def get_standard_bins(min_value,x,col,binsize):
    bins = np.arange(min_value, x[col].max()+binsize, binsize)
    return bins
In [21]:
# creates log scaled bins
def get_log_bins(x,col,log_binsize):
    bins = 10 ** np.arange(2.4, np.log10(x[col].max())+log_binsize, log_binsize)
    return bins

# creates standard histogram
def get_standard_histogram(bins,x_size,y_size,x,col,xt,yt,t,ax):
    plt.figure(figsize=[x_size, y_size])
    plt.hist(data = x, x = col, bins = bins)
    plt.xlabel(xt)
    plt.ylabel(yt)
    if len(ax) > 0:
        plt.axis(ax)
    plt.title(t)
    plt.show()

def draw_heatplot(x,xval,yval,xt,yt,t):
    plt.hist2d(data =x, x = xval, y = yval, cmap='viridis_r',norm=mpl.colors.LogNorm())
    plt.colorbar()
    plt.xlabel(xt)
    plt.ylabel(yt)
    plt.title(t);
In [25]:
# creates a heat plot
def draw_heatplot(x,yval,xval,xt,yt,t):
    x_counts = x.groupby([yval, xval]).size()
    x_counts = x_counts.reset_index(name=freq)
    x_counts = x_counts.pivot(index = yval, columns = xval, values = freq)
    sb.heatmap(x_counts)
    plt.xlabel(xt)
    plt.ylabel(yt)
    plt.title(t);

# plots a regression model
def draw_regression(xval,yval,x,cat,p,a,l,xt,yt,t):
    sb.lmplot( x=xval, y=yval, data=x, fit_reg=False, hue=cat, legend=False, palette=p, scatter_kws={"alpha":a,"s":15} )
    plt.legend(loc=l, markerscale=2)
    plt.xlabel(xt)
    plt.ylabel(yt)
    plt.title(t, loc='left')
    plt.show()

# filters the dataframe based on start time
def filter_dataframe(x,val1,val2):
    x_new = x[(x[st] >= val1 ) & (x[st] <= val2)]
    return x_new

all_files = glob.glob(folder_name + "/*.csv")
li = []
for filename in all_files:
    df = pd.read_csv(filename, index_col=None, header=0)
    li.append(df)
fordgobike = pd.concat(li, axis=0, ignore_index=True)

                    swn: ['Monday','Tuesday','Wednesday','Thursday','Friday','Saturday','Sunday']}

for var in ordinal_var_dict:

    df[var] = df[var].astype(ordered_var)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 2,570,833 bikerides of the San Francisco Bay area in the dataset with 22 features (duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, bike_id, user_type, member_birth_year, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip, start_month, start_weekday, start_month_name, start_weekday_name, start_hour, difference_station). Most variables are quantitative, but the variables start_station_name and end_station_name are of type string, the variables user_type, member_gender, start_month_name, and start_weekday_name are categorical, the variables start_time and end_time are of type datetime and the variable bike_share_for_all_trip is of type bool.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out what features are best for predicting when a bike ride will most likely take place and in what influences the duration of a bike ride.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that start_month_name, start_weekday_name, start_hour will have the strongest effect on the duration of a bike ride and the likeliness of renting a bike. I also think that gender, customer type and age will have effects on the duration though to a much smaller degree than the main effects of the afore mentioned features.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The distribution of the variable duration_sec, i.e. the duration of a trip in seconds is quite unusual in that it is highly skewed to the right. I performed a logarithmic transformation of the x-axis to discover some trends. The transformation showed that most trips were actually quite short.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The variables start_station_id, end_station_id and member_birth_year are numeric in nature but were stored as a float in the .csv file. So I removed the rows containing null values in these columns and converted them as an integer. Additionally, I converted the datatype of some variables such as user_type or member_gender as a category. Last but not least, I merged several csv files containing different time periods into one large csv file.

The duration in seconds had a correlation with the start time, i.e. the hour at which the bike trips started and the stations. Both diagrams showed a logarithmic relationship. Both the categorical variables customer types and gender show the same preference over the start time. They both tend to start a bike ride at the same hour, weekday or month.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Plotting the relationship of duration in seconds against the weekdays while taking the user type into account showed that the average duration of a rented bike is much higher regarding customers compared to subscribers. Apart from this, I found out that my main numeric variables of interest, namely the duration in seconds, start hour as well as the station ids have absolutely no linear relationship.

Insights¶

(I) Most trips are taken in the morning or afternoon until early evening hours.

(II) While customers would rather start their trips on weekends, subscribers clearly prefer to rent a bike during the work week.

(III) Between 2018 and 2019 the months March, April and October were the busiest ones.

(IV) While the average trip takes roughly 13 minutes, this is true for subscribers who rent a bike on weekends. If customers take a trip with a shared bike on weekends then the average duration increases to about 32 minutes.
